</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1436,1637,2022]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">
The genus 
<taxonomicName box="[284,394,1637,1661]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Paravelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[284,394,1637,1661]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Paravelia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was established by 
<bibRefCitation author="Breddin" box="[638,815,1637,1662]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" refString="Breddin, G. (1898) Studia hemipterologica. IV. Jahresberichte und Abhandlungen des Naturwissenschaftlichen Vereins in Magdeburg, 1896 - 1898, 149 - 163." type="book chapter" year="1898">
Breddin (
<number box="[749,807,1638,1662]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" value="1898.0">1898</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
to include two species described in the genus 
<taxonomicName authority="Latreille, 1804" authorityName="Latreille" authorityYear="1804" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Velia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1380,1436,1637,1661]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Velia</emphasis>
Latreille, 
<number box="[259,319,1674,1698]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" value="1804.0">1804</number>
</taxonomicName>
: 
<taxonomicName authority="Spinola, 1837" authorityName="Spinola" authorityYear="1837" box="[330,598,1673,1698]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Velia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="basalis">
<emphasis box="[330,436,1673,1697]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">V. basalis</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Spinola" box="[443,598,1673,1698]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" refString="Spinola, M. (1837) Essai sur les Genres d'Insectes Appartenants a l'Ordre des Hemipteres, Lin. ou Rhyngotes, Fab. et a la Section des Heteropteres, Dufour. Chez Yvez Gravier, Genes, 383 pp." type="book" year="1837">
Spinola, 
<number box="[542,598,1674,1698]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" value="1837.0">1837</number>
</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Berg, 1883" authorityName="Berg" authorityYear="1883" box="[652,911,1673,1698]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Paravelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="platensis">
<emphasis box="[652,778,1673,1697]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">V. platensis</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Berg" box="[785,911,1674,1698]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" refString="Berg, C. (1883) Addenda et emendanda ad Hemiptera Argentina. Anales de la Sociedad Cientifica Argentina, 16, 105 - 125." type="journal article" year="1883">
Berg, 
<number box="[852,911,1674,1698]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" value="1883.0">1883</number>
</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, in addition to a new species described by him, 
<taxonomicName authority="Breddin, 1898" authorityName="Breddin" authorityYear="1898" box="[151,473,1709,1734]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Paravelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="boliviana">
<emphasis box="[151,291,1709,1733]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">P. boliviana</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Breddin" box="[304,473,1709,1734]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" refString="Breddin, G. (1898) Studia hemipterologica. IV. Jahresberichte und Abhandlungen des Naturwissenschaftlichen Vereins in Magdeburg, 1896 - 1898, 149 - 163." type="book chapter" year="1898">
Breddin, 
<number box="[414,473,1710,1734]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" value="1898.0">1898</number>
</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
. Most of the other species which are currently included in 
<taxonomicName box="[1199,1309,1709,1733]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Paravelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1199,1309,1709,1733]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Paravelia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
were also originally described as 
<taxonomicName box="[411,467,1745,1769]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Velia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[411,467,1745,1769]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Velia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Later on, 
<bibRefCitation author="Hungerford" box="[589,813,1745,1770]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" refString="Hungerford, H. B. (1929 a) A new Velia from Arizona with notes on other species (Hemiptera-Veliidae). Annals of the Entomological Society of America, 22, 759 - 761." type="journal article" year="1929" yearSuffix="a">
Hungerford (
<number box="[734,792,1746,1770]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" value="1929.0">1929</number>
a)
</bibRefCitation>
transferred the species included by Breddin (
<taxonomicName box="[1322,1428,1745,1769]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Velia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="basalis">
<emphasis box="[1322,1428,1745,1769]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">P. basalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[151,278,1781,1805]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Paravelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="platensis">
<emphasis box="[151,278,1781,1805]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">P. platensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[331,464,1781,1805]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Paravelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="boliviana">
<emphasis box="[331,464,1781,1805]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">P. boliviana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) in 
<taxonomicName box="[508,618,1781,1805]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Paravelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[508,618,1781,1805]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Paravelia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
back to the genus 
<taxonomicName box="[826,882,1781,1805]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Velia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[826,882,1781,1805]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Velia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, dividing the American 
<emphasis box="[1153,1206,1781,1805]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Vel ia</emphasis>
into the four groups of species: 
<emphasis box="[291,505,1817,1841]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">
<taxonomicName box="[291,373,1817,1841]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Velia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="basalis">basalis</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[391,505,1817,1841]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Velia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brachialis">brachialis</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[526,644,1817,1841]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Velia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="inveruglas">
<emphasis box="[526,644,1817,1841]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">inveruglas</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[713,814,1817,1841]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Velia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="stagnalis">
<emphasis box="[713,814,1817,1841]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">stagnalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. In the same year, 
<bibRefCitation author="Hungerford" box="[1061,1292,1817,1842]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" refString="Hungerford, H. B. (1929 c) Some new semi-aquatic Hemiptera from South America with a record of stridulatory devices (Veliidae- Velia). Journal of Kansas Entomological Society, 2 (3), 50 - 59." type="journal article" year="1929" yearSuffix="c">
Hungerford (
<number box="[1213,1272,1818,1842]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" value="1929.0">1929</number>
c)
</bibRefCitation>
created the subgenus 
<taxonomicName authority="Hungerford, 1929" authorityName="Hungerford" authorityYear="1929" box="[262,608,1853,1878]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Stridulivelia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[262,400,1853,1877]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Stridulivelia</emphasis>
Hungerford, 
<number box="[552,608,1854,1878]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" value="1929.0">1929</number>
</taxonomicName>
to allocate six species: 
<taxonomicName authority="Champion, 1898" authorityName="Champion" authorityYear="1898" box="[876,1236,1853,1878]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Velia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cinctipes">
<emphasis box="[876,1039,1853,1877]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Velia cinctipes</emphasis>
Champion, 
<number box="[1177,1236,1854,1878]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" value="1898.0">1898</number>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="Hungerford, 1929" authorityName="Hungerford" authorityYear="1929" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Velia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="quadrispinosa">
<emphasis box="[1248,1436,1853,1877]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">V. quadrispinosa</emphasis>
Hungerford, 
<number box="[295,354,1890,1914]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" value="1929.0">1929</number>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="Hungerford, 1929" authorityName="Hungerford" authorityYear="1929" box="[365,667,1889,1914]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Velia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="raspa">
<emphasis box="[365,456,1890,1913]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">V. raspa</emphasis>
Hungerford, 
<number box="[608,667,1890,1914]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" value="1929.0">1929</number>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="Hungerford, 1929" authorityName="Hungerford" authorityYear="1929" box="[678,1025,1889,1914]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Velia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="stridulata">
<emphasis box="[678,815,1889,1913]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">V. stridulata</emphasis>
Hungerford, 
<number box="[966,1025,1890,1914]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" value="1929.0">1929</number>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="Hungerford, 1929" authorityName="Hungerford" authorityYear="1929" box="[1036,1361,1889,1914]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Velia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="strigosa">
<emphasis box="[1036,1153,1890,1913]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">V. strigosa</emphasis>
Hungerford, 
<number box="[1305,1361,1890,1914]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" value="1929.0">1929</number>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Hungerford, 1929" authorityName="Hungerford" authorityYear="1929" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Velia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="transversa">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">V. transversa</emphasis>
Hungerford, 
<number box="[420,479,1926,1950]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" value="1929.0">1929</number>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1436,1637,2022]" lastBlockId="3.[151,1437,151,2013]" lastPageId="3" lastPageNumber="4" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">
Thereafter, the genus 
<taxonomicName box="[451,561,1961,1985]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Paravelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[451,561,1961,1985]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Paravelia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was neglected by most researchers, which included all the subsequent new species in the genus 
<emphasis box="[381,434,1997,2021]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Vel ia</emphasis>
. After more than forty years, 
<bibRefCitation author="Polhemus" box="[770,963,1997,2022]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" refString="Polhemus, J. T. (1976) A reconsideration of the status of the genus Paravelia Breddin, with other notes and a check list of species (Veliidae: Heteroptera). Journal of the Kansas Entomological Society, 49 (4), 509 - 513." type="journal article" year="1976">
Polhemus (
<number box="[896,955,1997,2022]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" value="1976.0">1976</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
recognized that the 
<taxonomicName box="[1189,1245,1997,2021]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Velia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1189,1245,1997,2021]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Velia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species from the New World were not congeneric with those from the Old World, transferring all American species to the genus 
<taxonomicName box="[151,261,188,212]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Paravelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,261,188,212]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Paravelia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and elevating the subgenus 
<taxonomicName box="[627,765,188,212]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Stridulivelia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[627,765,188,212]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Stridulivelia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
to generic level. Later, 
<bibRefCitation author="Polhemus" box="[1072,1436,188,213]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" refString="Polhemus, J. T. &amp; Polhemus, D. A. (1993) Two new genera for New World Veliinae (Heteroptera: Veliidae). Journal of the New York Entomological Society, 101 (3), 391 - 398." type="journal article" year="1993">
Polhemus &amp; Polhemus (
<number box="[1370,1428,188,212]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" value="1993.0">1993</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
recognized two new genera within the species from 
<taxonomicName box="[744,854,224,248]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Paravelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[744,854,224,248]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Paravelia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, based mainly in sternum and acetabula structures: 
<taxonomicName box="[151,265,260,284]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Platyvelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,265,260,284]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Platyvelia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<typeStatus box="[282,332,260,284]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">type</typeStatus>
<taxonomicName authority="Stal, 1860" authorityName="Stal" authorityYear="1860" box="[342,649,260,285]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Velia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brachialis">
<emphasis box="[342,522,260,284]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Velia brachialis</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Stal" box="[532,649,260,285]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" refString="Stal, C. (1860) Bidrag till Rio Janeiro-Traktens Hemipter-Fauna. Kongliga Svenska Vetenskaps Akademiens Handlingar, 2, 1 - 84." type="journal article" year="1860">
StÃ¥l, 
<number box="[592,649,260,285]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" value="1860.0">1860</number>
</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
) and 
<taxonomicName box="[717,841,260,284]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Steinovelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[717,841,260,284]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Steinovelia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<typeStatus box="[859,909,260,284]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">type</typeStatus>
<taxonomicName authority="Burmeister, 1835" authorityName="Burmeister" authorityYear="1835" box="[918,1296,260,285]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Velia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="stagnalis">
<emphasis box="[918,1085,260,284]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Velia stagnalis</emphasis>
Burmeister, 
<number box="[1236,1296,260,285]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" value="1835.0">1835</number>
</taxonomicName>
). Even with reallocations and the creation of new genera, the genus 
<taxonomicName box="[786,896,296,320]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Paravelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[786,896,296,320]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Paravelia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
still seems to be paraphyletic (
<bibRefCitation author="Polhemus" box="[1251,1432,295,320]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" refString="Polhemus, J. T. (1976) A reconsideration of the status of the genus Paravelia Breddin, with other notes and a check list of species (Veliidae: Heteroptera). Journal of the Kansas Entomological Society, 49 (4), 509 - 513." type="journal article" year="1976">
Polhemus 
<number box="[1372,1432,295,320]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" value="1976.0">1976</number>
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Andersen" box="[151,325,332,357]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" refString="Andersen, N. M. (1982) The semiaquatic bugs (Hemiptera, Gerromorpha) phylogeny, adaptations, biogeography and classification. Entomonograph, 3, 1 - 455." type="journal article" year="1982">
Andersen 
<number box="[265,325,332,356]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" value="1982.0">1982</number>
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Polhemus" box="[336,659,332,357]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" refString="Polhemus, J. T. &amp; Polhemus, D. A. (1993) Two new genera for New World Veliinae (Heteroptera: Veliidae). Journal of the New York Entomological Society, 101 (3), 391 - 398." type="journal article" year="1993">
Polhemus &amp; Polhemus 
<number box="[599,659,332,356]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" value="1993.0">1993</number>
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="4" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,151,2013]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,372,367,392]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Redescription.</emphasis>
Thoracic polymorphism is very common, with macropterous (as in 
<figureCitation box="[1130,1191,367,392]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1376,1398]" captionTargetBox="[317,1269,414,1351]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[316,1270,411,1351]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 1. Paravelia amapaensis sp. nov. Male holotype, (A) dorsal view, (B) ventral view, (C) lateral view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/285782/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
Fig. 
<number box="[1181,1191,368,392]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" value="1.0">1</number>
</figureCitation>
A), brachypterous (as in 
<figureCitation box="[183,266,404,429]" captionStart="FIGURE 19" captionStartId="35.[151,250,1610,1632]" captionTargetBox="[283,1284,308,1583]" captionTargetId="figure@35.[279,1308,303,1587]" captionTargetPageId="35" captionText="FIGURE 19. Dorsal view, (A) Paravelia platensis (brachypterous), (B) P. spinifera, (C) P. williamsi, (D) ventral view of P. williamsi (arrow indicates the projections on sternite VII of male)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/285800/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
Fig. 
<number box="[238,266,404,428]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" value="19.0">19</number>
</figureCitation>
A), micropterous (as in 
<figureCitation box="[547,615,404,429]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="10.[151,250,1854,1876]" captionTargetBox="[297,1289,590,1830]" captionTargetId="figure@10.[293,1293,589,1833]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 5. Paravelia bipunctata sp. nov. (A) Dorsal view of micropterous male (holotype), (B) ventral view of micropterous male (holotype), (C) dorsal view of micropterous female (paratype), (D) dorsal view of macropterous female (paratype)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/285786/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
Fig. 
<number box="[602,615,404,429]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" value="5.0">5</number>
</figureCitation>
A) and apterous (as in 
<figureCitation box="[889,971,404,429]" captionStart="FIGURE 13" captionStartId="21.[151,250,1562,1584]" captionTargetBox="[251,1357,200,1536]" captionTargetId="figure@21.[221,1365,193,1541]" captionTargetPageId="21" captionText="FIGURE 13. Dorsal view, (A) Paravelia basalis (with apical macula), (B) P. basalis (without apical macula), (C) P. bi a e (holotype), (D) P. boliviana (apterous)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/285794/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
Fig. 
<number box="[944,971,404,428]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" value="13.0">13</number>
</figureCitation>
D) forms occurring. General body color usually brown, varying from dark, almost black tones, to yellowish or orange, with or without pruinose areas. Body length between 
<number box="[331,380,476,500]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" value="2.3">2.30</number>
and 9.00 mm, with or without modified setae similar to minute dark spines, which might be prominent or not, acute or blunt, named in literature as: minute conical black setae, minute peg-like points, black denticles, short black spinules, or flattened triangular tooth; herein considered small black denticles.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,151,2013]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,270,583,608]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Head.</emphasis>
Elongated in front of eyes and deflected; dorsally with longitudinal midline impressed and a pair of punctations or impressions on posterior region. Eyes globose, separated by a distance greater than eye width, located on posterior portion of head, adjacent to anterior margin of pronotum. Ocular setae usually present. Rostrum reaching mesocoxa.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,151,2013]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,294,727,752]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Thorax.</emphasis>
Pronotum in both apterous and alate forms long, covering meso- and usually almost entire metanotum, with a row of rounded punctations adjacent to anterior margin; posterior lobe covered by the same punctations, with posterior angle varying from rounded (as in 
<figureCitation box="[844,908,799,824]" captionStart="FIGURE 8" captionStartId="15.[151,250,1534,1556]" captionTargetBox="[334,1255,520,1508]" captionTargetId="figure@15.[328,1258,517,1513]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURE 8. Paravelia micromaculata sp. nov. Female holotype, (A) dorsal view, (B) ventral view, (C) lateral view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/285789/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
Fig. 
<number box="[895,908,800,824]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" value="8.0">8</number>
</figureCitation>
A) to triangular (as in 
<figureCitation box="[1158,1236,799,824]" captionStart="FIGURE 11" captionStartId="19.[151,250,1900,1922]" captionTargetBox="[286,1300,812,1878]" captionTargetId="figure@19.[282,1305,807,1879]" captionTargetPageId="19" captionText="FIGURE 11. Paravelia polhemusi sp. nov. Female holotype, (A) dorsal view, (B) ventral view, (C) lateral view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/285792/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
Fig. 
<number box="[1209,1236,800,824]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" value="11.0">11</number>
</figureCitation>
A), or acute (as in 
<figureCitation box="[151,231,836,861]" captionStart="FIGURE 17" captionStartId="30.[151,250,1475,1497]" captionTargetBox="[302,1288,208,1449]" captionTargetId="figure@30.[296,1291,195,1453]" captionTargetPageId="30" captionText="FIGURE 17. Dorsal view, (A) Paravelia foveata, (B) P. lanemeloi (paratype), (C) P. manausana, (D) P. nieseri (holotype)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/285798/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
Fig. 
<number box="[202,231,836,860]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" value="17.0">17</number>
</figureCitation>
D); anterior lobe in some species with a pair of maculae (as in 
<figureCitation box="[936,1015,836,861]" captionStart="FIGURE 17" captionStartId="30.[151,250,1475,1497]" captionTargetBox="[302,1288,208,1449]" captionTargetId="figure@30.[296,1291,195,1453]" captionTargetPageId="30" captionText="FIGURE 17. Dorsal view, (A) Paravelia foveata, (B) P. lanemeloi (paratype), (C) P. manausana, (D) P. nieseri (holotype)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/285798/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
Fig. 
<number box="[987,1015,836,860]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" value="17.0">17</number>
</figureCitation>
A), pruinose areas (as in 
<figureCitation box="[1296,1376,836,861]" captionStart="FIGURE 10" captionStartId="17.[151,250,1659,1681]" captionTargetBox="[236,1352,452,1634]" captionTargetId="figure@17.[229,1357,445,1637]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="FIGURE 10. Paravelia ornata sp. nov. (A) Dorsal view of male holotype, (B) ventral view of male paratype, (C) apex of male abdomen, (D) apex of female abdomen." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/285791/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
Fig. 
<number box="[1348,1376,836,860]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" value="10.0">10</number>
</figureCitation>
A) or pubescence (as in 
<figureCitation box="[379,453,871,896]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="6.[151,250,1937,1959]" captionTargetBox="[353,1234,949,1914]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[350,1236,949,1915]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 2. Paravelia bahiana sp. nov. (A) Dorsal view of male holotype, (B) dorsal view of female paratype, (C) lateral view of male, (D) ventral view of male abdomen apex." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/285783/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
Fig. 
<number box="[438,453,872,896]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" value="2.0">2</number>
</figureCitation>
A). Apterous and brachypterous forms usually with humeral angles not elevated. Macropterous form with wider pronotum, humeral angles well-developed and slightly elevated; forewings with four closed cells, reaching genital segments and usually dark brown; when closed, generally forming a pair of basal maculae, varying from white to yellowish, near humeral angles of pronotum; normally also another macula on apex of varied shape, which might or not reach the distal end of wings. Pro-, mesopleura, and prosternum with rounded punctations. Intersegmental region between meso- and metasternum generally with two pairs of small tubercles medially. Legs with or without spines; when present usually on hind femur, organized or not in rows, with varying numbers; all legs with three tarsomeres and falcate claws; arolia setae-like; tarsomere I generally very small; tarsomere II of midleg usually very long, reaching to five times the length of tarsomere I in some cases; tarsomere III of all legs cylindrical or subcylindrical, with parallel margins (except for 
<taxonomicName box="[1028,1166,1196,1220]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Paravelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bullialata">
<emphasis box="[1028,1166,1196,1220]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">P. bullialata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[1224,1370,1196,1220]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Paravelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="splendoris">
<emphasis box="[1224,1370,1196,1220]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">P. splendoris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, with slightly divergent margins).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,151,2013]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,323,1268,1293]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Abdomen.</emphasis>
Generally without pruinose areas, with posterior angle of last connexival segment developed (as in 
<figureCitation box="[151,239,1303,1328]" captionStart="FIGURE 12" captionStartId="20.[151,250,1096,1118]" captionTargetBox="[253,1335,197,1070]" captionTargetId="figure@20.[249,1338,193,1074]" captionTargetPageId="20" captionText="FIGURE 12. Paravelia ornata sp. nov. (A) Lateral view of first genital segment of male, (B) lateral view of genital capsule of male, (C) lateral view of paramere, (D) lateral view of female abdomen. Paravelia polhemusi sp. nov. (E) Lateral view of female abdomen, (F) ventral view of hind femur of female." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/285793/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
Fig. 
<number box="[211,239,1304,1328]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" value="12.0">12</number>
</figureCitation>
D) or not (as in 
<figureCitation box="[460,550,1303,1328]" captionStart="FIGURE 12" captionStartId="20.[151,250,1096,1118]" captionTargetBox="[253,1335,197,1070]" captionTargetId="figure@20.[249,1338,193,1074]" captionTargetPageId="20" captionText="FIGURE 12. Paravelia ornata sp. nov. (A) Lateral view of first genital segment of male, (B) lateral view of genital capsule of male, (C) lateral view of paramere, (D) lateral view of female abdomen. Paravelia polhemusi sp. nov. (E) Lateral view of female abdomen, (F) ventral view of hind femur of female." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/285793/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
Fig. 
<number box="[521,550,1304,1328]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" value="12.0">12</number>
</figureCitation>
E). 
<emphasis box="[598,666,1304,1328]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Males</emphasis>
â€”with connexives horizontal to slightly elevated; apterous and brachypterous forms with six visible tergites (as in 
<figureCitation box="[727,811,1340,1365]" captionStart="FIGURE 14" captionStartId="24.[151,250,1526,1548]" captionTargetBox="[257,1336,215,1486]" captionTargetId="figure@24.[244,1342,193,1504]" captionTargetPageId="24" captionText="FIGURE 14. Dorsal view, (A) Paravelia bullialata, (B) P. capillata, (C) P. capixaba (macropterous), (D) P. capixaba (apterous)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/285795/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
Figs 
<number box="[782,811,1340,1364]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" value="14.0">14</number>
</figureCitation>
D, 
<number box="[845,874,1340,1364]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" value="18.0">18</number>
D); sternite VII sometimes bearing projections (as in 
<figureCitation box="[182,264,1375,1400]" captionStart="FIGURE 19" captionStartId="35.[151,250,1610,1632]" captionTargetBox="[283,1284,308,1583]" captionTargetId="figure@35.[279,1308,303,1587]" captionTargetPageId="35" captionText="FIGURE 19. Dorsal view, (A) Paravelia platensis (brachypterous), (B) P. spinifera, (C) P. williamsi, (D) ventral view of P. williamsi (arrow indicates the projections on sternite VII of male)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/285800/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
Fig. 
<number box="[236,264,1376,1400]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" value="19.0">19</number>
</figureCitation>
D) or small lobes on posterior margin (as in 
<figureCitation box="[781,850,1375,1400]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="11.[151,250,997,1019]" captionTargetBox="[273,1315,201,972]" captionTargetId="figure@11.[266,1321,193,976]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURE 6. Paravelia bilobata sp. nov. First genital segment of male: (A) dorsal view, (B) lateral view, (C) ventral view. (D) Ventral view of male abdomen apex, (E) lateral view of genital capsule of male, (F) frontal view of projections on male proctiger. Paravelia bipunctata sp. nov. First genital segment of male, (G) dorsal view, (H) lateral view. (I) Lateral view of genital capsule of male." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/285787/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
Fig. 
<number box="[835,850,1375,1400]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" value="6.0">6</number>
</figureCitation>
D); proctiger with (as in 
<figureCitation box="[1139,1226,1375,1400]" captionStart="FIGURE 20" captionStartId="36.[151,250,1978,2000]" captionTargetBox="[203,1383,582,1952]" captionTargetId="figure@36.[198,1389,577,1957]" captionTargetPageId="36" captionText="FIGURE 20. Lateral view of genital capsule of male, (A) P. nieseri, (B) P. platensis, paramere in posterior view, (C) P. recens, (D) P. rotundanotata, (E) P. spinifera, (F) P. splendoris, (G) P. williamsi." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/285801/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
Figs 
<number box="[1196,1226,1376,1400]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" value="20.0">20</number>
</figureCitation>
A,D,G) or without projections (as in 
<figureCitation box="[354,441,1412,1437]" captionStart="FIGURE 20" captionStartId="36.[151,250,1978,2000]" captionTargetBox="[203,1383,582,1952]" captionTargetId="figure@36.[198,1389,577,1957]" captionTargetPageId="36" captionText="FIGURE 20. Lateral view of genital capsule of male, (A) P. nieseri, (B) P. platensis, paramere in posterior view, (C) P. recens, (D) P. rotundanotata, (E) P. spinifera, (F) P. splendoris, (G) P. williamsi." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/285801/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
Figs 
<number box="[410,441,1412,1436]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" value="20.0">20</number>
</figureCitation>
C,F); parameres symmetrical, thin or wide, rich in setae or not. 
<emphasis box="[1162,1257,1412,1436]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Females</emphasis>
â€”with elevated connexives; apterous and brachypterous forms with seven visible tergites (as in 
<figureCitation box="[1086,1160,1447,1472]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="10.[151,250,1854,1876]" captionTargetBox="[297,1289,590,1830]" captionTargetId="figure@10.[293,1293,589,1833]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 5. Paravelia bipunctata sp. nov. (A) Dorsal view of micropterous male (holotype), (B) ventral view of micropterous male (holotype), (C) dorsal view of micropterous female (paratype), (D) dorsal view of macropterous female (paratype)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/285786/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
Figs 
<number box="[1146,1160,1447,1472]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" value="5.0">5</number>
</figureCitation>
C, 
<number box="[1196,1224,1448,1472]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" value="13.0">13</number>
D), generally with connexives reflected over abdomen; proctiger and gonocoxae with or without small black denticles.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="4" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,151,2013]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,332,1519,1544]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Discussion.</emphasis>
Very similar to the Palaearctic genus 
<emphasis box="[755,808,1520,1544]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Ve l i a</emphasis>
Latreille, 
<number box="[926,982,1520,1544]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" value="1804.0">1804</number>
and the South American genus 
<emphasis box="[1340,1436,1520,1544]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Oiovelia</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Drake" box="[151,559,1556,1581]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" refString="Drake, C. J. &amp; Maldonado-Capriles, J. (1952) Water-striders from Territorio Amazonas of Venezuela (Hemiptera: Hydrometridae, Veliidae). Great Basin Naturalist, 12, 47 - 54." type="journal article" year="1952">
Drake &amp; Maldonado-Capriles, 
<number box="[500,559,1556,1581]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" value="1952.0">1952</number>
</bibRefCitation>
. In 
<emphasis box="[600,653,1556,1580]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Ve l i a</emphasis>
the female proctiger covers the gonocoxae and genital opening; male hind femur bears two widely separated spines on inner surface; and the macropterous form has another median macula, in addition to the basal and apical maculae. In 
<taxonomicName box="[830,940,1628,1652]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Paravelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[830,940,1628,1652]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Paravelia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the female proctiger does not cover the gonocoxae and genital opening; the spines of male hind femur, if present, are more than two and not widely separated; and the macropterous form usually has only a pair of basal maculae and an apical macula. 
<taxonomicName box="[1325,1435,1700,1724]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Paravelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1325,1435,1700,1724]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Paravelia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from 
<emphasis box="[296,392,1736,1760]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Oiovelia</emphasis>
mainly by the shape of tarsomere III, being cylindrical and with parallel margins, whereas they are expanded and with divergent lateral margins in 
<emphasis box="[785,881,1772,1796]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Oiovelia</emphasis>
. In addition, the macropterous form in 
<taxonomicName box="[1325,1435,1772,1796]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Paravelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1325,1435,1772,1796]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Paravelia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has a pair of basal maculae, and another apical macula on forewings, whereas in 
<emphasis box="[1128,1225,1808,1832]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Oiovelia</emphasis>
the macropterous specimens have only a pair of basal maculae, with remainder of wing at most pruinose. Representatives of 
<taxonomicName box="[151,262,1880,1904]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Paravelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,262,1880,1904]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Paravelia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are frequently collected in low numbers, in lentic environments, like temporary pools, slow portions of streams, lakes, or even on water accumulated in bromeliad tanks; whereas the 
<emphasis box="[1076,1173,1916,1940]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Oiovelia</emphasis>
species are preferably inhabitants of foam masses formed on streams.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="4" lastPageNumber="5" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,151,2013]" lastBlockId="4.[151,1436,151,356]" lastPageId="4" lastPageNumber="5" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,321,1988,2013]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
The genus can be differentiated from other Neotropical 
<taxonomicName box="[959,1051,1988,2013]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Veliinae">Veliinae</taxonomicName>
by the following set of characters (from 
<bibRefCitation author="Andersen" box="[222,396,151,176]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" refString="Andersen, N. M. (1982) The semiaquatic bugs (Hemiptera, Gerromorpha) phylogeny, adaptations, biogeography and classification. Entomonograph, 3, 1 - 455." type="journal article" year="1982">
Andersen 
<number box="[337,396,152,176]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" value="1982.0">1982</number>
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Polhemus" box="[409,735,151,176]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" refString="Polhemus, J. T. &amp; Polhemus, D. A. (1993) Two new genera for New World Veliinae (Heteroptera: Veliidae). Journal of the New York Entomological Society, 101 (3), 391 - 398." type="journal article" year="1993">
Polhemus &amp; Polhemus 
<number box="[674,735,152,176]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" value="1993.0">1993</number>
</bibRefCitation>
): middle and hind tarsi with setae-shaped arolia, and only two falcate claws; abdominal segments without transverse sulci; hind femora and connexival margin without stridulatory devices; metasternum without lateral tubercles; middle leg with tarsomere II usually 
<number box="[1246,1288,223,248]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" value="4.5" valueMax="5.0" valueMin="4.0">4â€“5</number>
times longer than the length of tarsomere I, and tarsomere III of all legs subcylindrical, with parallel margins (as in 
<figureCitation box="[1305,1370,260,285]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1376,1398]" captionTargetBox="[317,1269,414,1351]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[316,1270,411,1351]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 1. Paravelia amapaensis sp. nov. Male holotype, (A) dorsal view, (B) ventral view, (C) lateral view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/285782/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">
Fig. 
<number box="[1357,1370,260,284]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" value="1.0">1</number>
</figureCitation>
); and macropterous form usually with a basal macula and another apical macula (as in 
<figureCitation box="[1096,1165,295,320]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1376,1398]" captionTargetBox="[317,1269,414,1351]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[316,1270,411,1351]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 1. Paravelia amapaensis sp. nov. Male holotype, (A) dorsal view, (B) ventral view, (C) lateral view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/285782/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">
Figs 
<number box="[1155,1165,296,320]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" value="1.0">1</number>
</figureCitation>
A, 
<number box="[1206,1220,296,320]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" value="2.0">2</number>
Aâ€“B); body length 
<number box="[151,200,332,356]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" value="2.3">2.30</number>
â€“9.00 mm.
</paragraph>
